    <item><title>ChristianMahnke.de: Summer evening in Worpswede (Sommerabend in Worpswede) by Cornelius Rogge (1868 – 1949)</title>
        <link>https://christianmahnke.de/post/print-cornelius-rogge</link>
        <pubDate>Mon, 30 Dec 2024 14:50:44 +0100</pubDate>
        <guid>https://projektemacher.org/en/post/christianmahnke/post/print-cornelius-rogge/</guid>
        <description>&lt;p&gt;I found an colourised etching by &lt;a href=&#34;https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/K%C3%BCnstlerkolonie_D%C3%B6tlingen#Cornelius_Rogge&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Cornelius Rogge&lt;/a&gt; (1868 – 1949)&amp;hellip;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div&gt;Print&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Signature&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Cornelius Rogge was an etcher in the &lt;a href=&#34;https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/K%C3%BCnstlerkolonie_D%C3%B6tlingen&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;artists&amp;rsquo; colony of Dötlingen&lt;/a&gt; and from 1922 in &lt;a href=&#34;https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Worpswede&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Worpswede&lt;/a&gt;, about 60 kilometres away. His motifs mainly depict the North German landscape and he was the brother of &lt;a href=&#34;https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emy_Rogge&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Emy Rogge&lt;/a&gt;. After working as an export merchant, the period of inflation led him to use his self-taught skills to earn a living as an artist.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The picture shows the entrance and windows of a house on a summer evening in Worpswede.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The website of the Dötlingen Foundation also has an article about &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.kuenstlerkolonie-doetlingen.de/cornelius-rogge.html&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Cornelius Rogge&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item>
    <item><title>ChristianMahnke.de: Moscow drawings by Heinrich Sielken (1874 - 1942)</title>
        <link>https://christianmahnke.de/post/drawing-heinrich-sielken</link>
        <pubDate>Mon, 30 Dec 2024 14:50:44 +0100</pubDate>
        <guid>https://projektemacher.org/en/post/christianmahnke/post/drawing-heinrich-sielken/</guid>
        <description>&lt;p&gt;I came across two drawings by &lt;a href=&#34;https://glass-portal.hier-im-netz.de/hs/s-z/sielken_heinrich.htm&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Heinrich Sielken&lt;/a&gt; (1874 - 1942)&amp;hellip;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div&gt;Sheet 1&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Sheet 2&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Heinrich Sielken was an architect who was born in Hanover and worked in Bremen from 1920. In 1927 he published an article in the Deutsche Bauzeitung (&lt;a href=&#34;https://delibra.bg.polsl.pl/Content/14217/P-388_1927_58.pdf&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;61. Jahrgang. 1927, Nr. 58, S. 481-485&lt;/a&gt;) about the Holy Trinity Church of St Sergius near Moscow. The drawings and the article were most likely created on the same journey.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The first drawing is a view across the &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moskva_%28river%29&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Moskva River&lt;/a&gt; to the &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kremlin&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Kremlin&lt;/a&gt;. It shows the &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Moscow_Kremlin_towers#Taynitskaya&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Taynitskaya tower (Тайницкая башня)&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cathedral_of_the_Archangel&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Cathedral of the Archangel&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivan_the_Great_Bell_Tower&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Ivan the Great Bell Tower&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class=&#34;iframe-wrapper&#34; id=&#34;_iframe-2c8439f08eb5daf8ffcd665bb0c67c28&#34;&gt;
  &lt;div class=&#34;iframe&#34;&gt;
